arst's Magazine (1918) -- t"A Farewell Letter to the Kaiser from Every Woman,"Washington Post (1918) -- t"The New America, the American Jewish Woman: A Symposium," American Hebrew (1919) -- t"What the Newest New Woman Is," Ladies' Home Journal (1920) -- tPART VII. Prohibition and Sexuality -- t"What Shall We Do with Jazz?" Atlanta Constitution (1922) -- t"Exodo de Una Flapper" [Exodus of a Flapper], Hispano América (1925) -- t"Sweet Sexteen," Life (1926) -- t"The 'Outrageous' Younger Set: A Young Girl Attempts to Explain Some of the Forces That Brought It into Being," Vanity Fair (1927) -- t"Fumando Espero" [Smoking I Wait], Gráfico (1927) -- tPART VIII. Consumer Culture, Leisure Culture, and Technology -- t"The Eternal Feminine," Printers' Ink (1901) -- t"Battle Ax Plug," Santa Fe New Mexican (1896) -- t"The Athletic Woman," Good Housekeeping (1912) -- t"The Woman of the Future," Good Housekeeping (1912) -- t"The Woman's Magazine," Masses (1915) -- t"Famous Bobbed-Hair Beauties,"Negro World (1924) -- t"From Ping Pong to Pants," Photoplay (1927) -- t"Daughters of the Sky," Delineator (1929) -- tPART IX. Evolution, Birth Control, and Eugenics -- t"Effeminate Men and Masculine Women,"New York Medical Journal (1900) -- t"The Evolution of Sex in Mind," Independent (1901) -- t"The New Woman Monkey," Life (1906); and "Evolution," Life (1913) -- t"Flapper Americana Novissima," Atlantic Monthly (1922) -- t"The New Woman: In the Political World She Is the Source of All Reform Legislation and the One Power That Is Humanizing the World," Negro World (1924) -- t"The New Woman in the Making," Current History (1927) -- t"La Mujer Nueva" [The New Woman], Gráfico (1929) -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Editor0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn North America between 1894 and 1930, the rise of the "New Woman" sparked controversy on both sides of the Atlantic and around the world. As she demanded a public voice as well as private fulfillment through work, education, and politics, American journalists debated and defined her. Who was she and where did she come from? Was she to be celebrated as the agent of progress or reviled as a traitor to the traditional family? Over time, the dominant version of the American New Woman became typified as white, educated, and middle class: the suffragist, progressive reformer, and bloomer-wearing bicyclist. By the 1920s, the jazz-dancing flapper epitomized her. Yet she also had many other faces. Bringing together a diverse range of essays from the periodical press of the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Martha H. Patterson shows how the New Woman differed according to region, class, politics, race, ethnicity, and historical circumstance. In addition to the New Woman's prevailing incarnations, she appears here as a gun-wielding heroine, imperialist symbol, assimilationist icon, entrepreneur, socialist, anarchist, thief, vamp, and eugenicist. Together, these readings redefine our understanding of the New Woman and her cultural impact.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aFeminismxHistoryxUnited States. 0aFeminismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMinority womenxHistoryxUnited States. 0aMinority womenzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomenxHistoryxUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomen's rightsxHistoryxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxUSA. 0aWomen's rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aPatterson, Martha H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/is